  "prompt": "Which is correct, \"five hundred dollars\" or \"five hundred dollar\"?",
  "response": "Both \"five hundred dollars\" and \"five hundred dollar\" are correct, but they are used in different contexts based on their grammatical roles in a sentence. Here's a breakdown of when to use each form:\n\n1. **\"Five hundred dollars\"** _(plural noun form)_:\n   - **Usage**: When referring to the amount of money directly.\n   - **Example Sentences**:\n     - *I have five hundred dollars in my bank account.*\n     - *The laptop costs five hundred dollars.*\n\n2. **\"Five hundred dollar\"** _(adjective form)_:\n   - **Usage**: When using the amount as an adjective to describe a noun.\n   - **Example Sentences**:\n     - *She bought a five hundred dollar watch.*\n     - *They made a five hundred dollar donation to the charity.*\n     - *He received a five hundred dollar check.*\n\n**Summary:**\n- Use **\"dollars\"** when stating the amount as a standalone figure.\n- Use **\"dollar\"** when the amount is describing or modifying another noun.\n\n### Additional Examples:\n\n- **Correct**: *The project will cost five hundred dollars.*\n- **Correct**: *They purchased a five hundred dollar instrument.*\n- **Incorrect**: *He owes me five hundred dollar.* (Should be \"five hundred dollars.\")\n- **Incorrect**: *She won a five hundred dollars prize.* (Should be \"a five hundred dollar prize.\")\n\nUnderstanding the distinction between when to use the plural noun form versus the adjective form will help ensure clarity and grammatical correctness in your writing and speaking.",
